Assignment¶

Univariate Linear Regression on the California Housing Prices Dataset¶

Framing the Problem¶

The goal is to build and evaluate univariate linear regression models to understand how individual features (median income, population, number of households) influence the median house value in California. This is a foundational exercise in machine learning, intended to teach you how to explore data, visualize relationships, build models, and interpret their performance.

California Housing Prices Dataset on Kaggle

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Set the plotting style
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# Plotting function
def plot_scatter(x, y, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    sns.scatterplot(data=df, x=x, y=y, alpha=0.4)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.ylabel(y)
    plt.show()

plot_scatter('median_income', 'median_house_value', 'Median Income vs Median House Value')
plot_scatter('population', 'median_house_value', 'Population vs Median House Value')
plot_scatter('households', 'median_house_value', 'Number of Households vs Median House Value')

Description of Variables¶

Variable Description Range Notes
median_income Median income of residents in block (in tens of thousands) ~0.5 to 15 Strongest correlation with house value
population Total population in the block ~3 to 35,000 High variance, weak correlation
households Number of households in the block ~1 to 6,000 Similar trend to population
median_house_value Median house price in USD ~15,000 to 500,001 Capped at 500,001 in dataset

Linear Regression Modeling¶

In [23]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error
import numpy as np

# Function to train a model and return coefficients and metrics
def run_linear_regression(X_column):
    X = df[[X_column]]
    y = df['median_house_value']
    
    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X, y)
    
    intercept = model.intercept_
    slope = model.coef_[0]
    
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y, y_pred)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y, y_pred)
    
    return model, intercept, slope, mse, mae, y_pred

# Run models
results = {}
for feature in ['median_income', 'population', 'households']:
    results[feature] = run_linear_regression(feature)

Regression Plots with Line¶

# Plotting function with regression line and metrics
def plot_regression(feature, model, intercept, slope, mse, mae):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    sns.scatterplot(x=df[feature], y=df['median_house_value'], alpha=0.4)
    plt.plot(df[feature], model.predict(df[[feature]]), color='red')
    plt.title(f'{feature} vs Median House Value')
    plt.xlabel(feature)
    plt.ylabel('median_house_value')
    
    # Add text box with model metrics
    plt.text(0.05, 0.95,
             f"Intercept: {intercept:.2f}\nSlope: {slope:.2f}\nMSE: {mse:.2f}\nMAE: {mae:.2f}",
             transform=plt.gca().transAxes,
             fontsize=10,
             verticalalignment='top',
             bbox=dict(boxstyle="round", facecolor="wheat", alpha=0.5))
    
    plt.show()

# Plot each regression model (unpack only 6 values, ignore y_pred)
for feature in results:
    model, intercept, slope, mse, mae, _ = results[feature]
    plot_regression(feature, model, intercept, slope, mse, mae)

Summary & Conclusion¶

Comparison of Models¶

Feature R² (visual strength) MSE MAE Interpretation
median_income Strong Lowest Lowest Best predictor of house value
population Weak High High Poor predictor due to noise
households Weak/Moderate Mid Mid Slightly better than population

Insights¶

  • Median income is the most powerful indicator of median house values in California. This aligns with economic theory that income levels drive affordability and property prices.

  • Population and households are less useful for prediction on their own and likely need to be combined with other variables for better accuracy.

  • Additional transformations or multivariate models may help better capture the complexity in the data.
